{"name":"Common.Real.Floor","instances":[],"imports":["Init","Mathlib.Algebra.BigOperators.Basic","Mathlib.Data.Real.Basic","Mathlib.Data.Finset.Basic"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/jrpotter/bookshelf/blob/49bd4871fe370bf917f7d3668819d716532dbe39/Common/Real/Floor.lean#L106-L146","name":"Real.Floor.floor_mul_eq_sum_range_floor_add_index_div","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Common/Real/Floor.html#Real.Floor.floor_mul_eq_sum_range_floor_add_index_div","doc":"### Hermite's Identity\n\nThe following decomposes the floor of a multiplication into a sum of floors.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/jrpotter/bookshelf/blob/49bd4871fe370bf917f7d3668819d716532dbe39/Common/Real/Floor.lean#L93-L96","name":"Real.Floor.Hermite.partition_eq_Ico_zero_one","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Common/Real/Floor.html#Real.Floor.Hermite.partition_eq_Ico_zero_one","doc":"The indexed union of the family of sets of a `partition` is equal to `[0, 1)`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/jrpotter/bookshelf/blob/49bd4871fe370bf917f7d3668819d716532dbe39/Common/Real/Floor.lean#L83-L88","name":"Real.Floor.Hermite.Ico_zero_one_subset_partition","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Common/Real/Floor.html#Real.Floor.Hermite.Ico_zero_one_subset_partition","doc":"`[0, 1)` is a subset of the indexed union of the family of sets of a `partition`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/jrpotter/bookshelf/blob/49bd4871fe370bf917f7d3668819d716532dbe39/Common/Real/Floor.lean#L50-L78","name":"Real.Floor.Hermite.partition_subset_Ico_zero_one","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Common/Real/Floor.html#Real.Floor.Hermite.partition_subset_Ico_zero_one","doc":"The indexed union of the family of sets of a `partition` is a subset of `[0, 1)`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/jrpotter/bookshelf/blob/49bd4871fe370bf917f7d3668819d716532dbe39/Common/Real/Floor.lean#L42-L45","name":"Real.Floor.Hermite.fract_mem_partition","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Common/Real/Floor.html#Real.Floor.Hermite.fract_mem_partition","doc":"The fractional portion of any real number always exists in some member of the\nindexed family of sets formed by any `partition`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/jrpotter/bookshelf/blob/49bd4871fe370bf917f7d3668819d716532dbe39/Common/Real/Floor.lean#L36-L36","name":"Real.Floor.Hermite.partition","kind":"def","docLink":"./Common/Real/Floor.html#Real.Floor.Hermite.partition","doc":"A partition of `[0, 1)` that looks as follows:\n\n```\n[0, 1/n), [1/n, 2/n), ..., [(n-1)/n, 1)\n```\n\nThis is expected to be used as an indexing function of a union of sets, e.g.\n`⋃ i ∈ Finset.range n, partition n i`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/jrpotter/bookshelf/blob/49bd4871fe370bf917f7d3668819d716532dbe39/Common/Real/Floor.lean#L15-L17","name":"Real.Floor.fract_mem_Ico_zero_one","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Common/Real/Floor.html#Real.Floor.fract_mem_Ico_zero_one","doc":"The fractional portion of any real number is always in `[0, 1)`.\n"}]}